WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:25.580
Hi, everyone, and welcome to our new podcast, Thinking With.

00:00:27.380 --> 00:00:31.040
There are three of us that are thinking.

00:00:34.120 --> 00:00:35.020
You're fired!

00:00:35.380 --> 00:00:37.100
I know. All right, let's try that again.

00:00:37.580 --> 00:00:38.880
John's dancing in the background.

00:00:39.220 --> 00:00:40.660
I know. I'm just trying to fuck with him.

00:00:40.820 --> 00:00:41.460
They can't see that.

00:00:45.420 --> 00:00:49.860
Hi, everyone, and welcome to our new podcast, Thinking With.

00:00:50.240 --> 00:00:54.100
We are Nate DeProspo, John Muckelbauer, and Nathaniel Street.

00:00:55.320 --> 00:01:02.280
Nate is a current graduate student at the University of South Carolina in rhetoric and composition,

00:01:02.280 --> 00:01:12.000
and he is in the process of writing his dissertation on the role of new materialism and post-humanism in rhetorical theory,

00:01:12.120 --> 00:01:16.240
and especially its relationship to Karen Barad and Hegel.

00:01:17.060 --> 00:01:25.980
John Muckelbauer is an associate professor at the University of South Carolina and on Nate's dissertation committee.

00:01:26.920 --> 00:01:38.020
He has a well-known book, The Future of an Invention, and someday will publish his second book on style,

00:01:38.020 --> 00:01:42.660
style, which you will hear us talk about here and there and in the podcast.

00:01:43.800 --> 00:01:52.100
And I am Nathaniel Street, and I am an assistant professor at Mount St. Vincent University in Nova Scotia,

00:01:52.180 --> 00:01:59.100
but I finished my graduate work at the University of South Carolina in 2016,

00:01:59.100 --> 00:02:02.380
and John was the advisor for my dissertation.

00:02:02.380 --> 00:02:12.760
So I was, I mean, because it started with you guys reading my proposal for my dissertation,

00:02:13.380 --> 00:02:18.440
and I kind of referenced Hegel opaquely or through Žižek.

00:02:18.620 --> 00:02:26.920
Like, through Žižek and Malabou, I was referencing the Hegelian system and using it as kind of a launching pad

00:02:26.920 --> 00:02:33.500
into this different theoretical apparatus than I was, like, sort of trained in or that I was really familiar with.

00:02:33.500 --> 00:02:40.580
But I was kind of diving into this apparatus or whatever you want to call it in order to, as you guys know,

00:02:41.040 --> 00:02:48.120
challenge or complicate what I see as a more dominant strain of thinking in rhetoric and composition.

00:02:48.440 --> 00:02:54.940
You could call it materialist or post-humanist, but to me it's just, like, trying to synthesize those

00:02:54.940 --> 00:03:04.400
and now trying to back away from my polemical reaction against post-humanism through Hegel, through Butler, through Foucault.

00:03:04.880 --> 00:03:10.040
I mean, and so you guys, I think, liked the proposal or were interested in it,

00:03:10.320 --> 00:03:13.580
and so that was kind of the inception of this podcast.

00:03:13.580 --> 00:03:20.240
And I think it's really grown, I mean, I've really grown personally in terms of my disposition

00:03:20.240 --> 00:03:24.060
and my approach towards those different discourses.

00:03:24.500 --> 00:03:29.460
And so, I mean, you guys have, like, really helped that process, thinking through the dissertation

00:03:29.460 --> 00:03:34.340
and then through your guys' various dispositions as well, you know.

00:03:34.340 --> 00:03:41.460
Yeah, I mean, I would say in some ways that the podcast was born of a couple of impulses.

00:03:41.460 --> 00:03:48.460
So, I mean, the first, I don't think we can understate the role of the pandemic in the genesis of the podcast.

00:03:48.460 --> 00:04:00.340
That, you know, the three of us felt pretty intellectually isolated and, you know, some of the first initial ideas

00:04:00.340 --> 00:04:07.980
were to try to coordinate reading groups or opportunities for scholars across rhetoric and composition to, you know,

00:04:07.980 --> 00:04:09.580
talk about this or that text.

00:04:09.580 --> 00:04:19.260
And what it eventually fell into was the three of us doing this reading group inspired by Nate's dissertation proposal defense.

00:04:20.220 --> 00:04:24.340
And so that was the kind of the agitation.

00:04:24.460 --> 00:04:33.860
And I think there was also a certain dissatisfaction with the state of institutionalized education

00:04:33.860 --> 00:04:40.020
that, you know, we wanted to imagine an engagement with these texts.

00:04:40.020 --> 00:04:42.560
And in this case, it turned out to be Hegel to begin with.

00:04:43.160 --> 00:04:51.020
Imagine an engagement with them that isn't simply about trying to explain or demonstrate a mastery of the text

00:04:51.020 --> 00:04:58.300
or even develop a mastery of the text, but to imagine an educational pedagogical orientation to reading and conversation

00:04:58.300 --> 00:05:09.040
that is first and foremost designed to or is interested in provoking thinking between us, between us and the text.

00:05:09.220 --> 00:05:13.320
And, you know, that's where the title Thinking With came out of, where, you know,

00:05:14.100 --> 00:05:19.540
as anybody who listens to this podcast will quickly understand, none of us are experts on Hegel.

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:25.100
We often aren't talking about Hegel or the text explicitly.

00:05:25.100 --> 00:05:30.340
We're not trying to explain the concepts or giving context for Hegel's philosophy,

00:05:30.340 --> 00:05:40.220
that we are using the chunks of readings that drive each of the episodes as catalysts for thinking about a whole range of things.

00:05:40.820 --> 00:05:44.860
A lot of it just so happens to be Hegel explicitly, but a lot of it isn't.

00:05:45.580 --> 00:05:51.480
I mean, John, you had some other, like, a few episodes back when we were talking about doing this introduction,

00:05:51.700 --> 00:06:00.740
you kind of expanded on the institutional, like, situation and how this offered us a different kind of approach.

00:06:00.900 --> 00:06:03.100
And you just hit on that a little bit.

00:06:03.180 --> 00:06:11.480
But, I mean, you were saying basically that the way that the institution functioned doesn't allow conversations like this really to happen,

00:06:11.640 --> 00:06:14.940
either because of the authoritative position of the teacher or the instructor.

00:06:14.940 --> 00:06:18.700
I don't know, you phrased it much more interestingly than I just tried to summarize.

00:06:19.740 --> 00:06:25.800
Yeah, I mean, I don't remember what I said, but if I'm responding to that question, I mean, you know,

00:06:25.840 --> 00:06:29.400
I would reemphasize, begin by reemphasizing the thing that Nathaniel just said,

00:06:29.460 --> 00:06:34.860
which is this is not an introduction to, and it's not an attempt to teach in that sense.

00:06:35.340 --> 00:06:39.640
So, you know, teaching is, like, here are the basic principles that you need to understand.

00:06:39.820 --> 00:06:44.520
I mean, none of us are Hegel experts, and none of us are philosophers, right?

00:06:44.620 --> 00:06:45.620
Like, we aren't.

00:06:47.020 --> 00:06:51.140
So it's not an introduction to, and it doesn't serve that function.

00:06:51.300 --> 00:06:54.920
But it is also not, like, an advanced level either, right?

00:06:54.980 --> 00:06:58.260
It's not, you know, it's not like, okay, well, if it's not an introduction to,

00:06:58.320 --> 00:07:00.280
it must be something that's a higher level.

00:07:00.280 --> 00:07:01.780
It's like, it's not really that either.

00:07:01.940 --> 00:07:05.180
It is much more just of a mix mash of theory.

00:07:05.820 --> 00:07:12.300
So we are a bunch of folks at different stages of our intellectual and professional careers, right?

00:07:12.380 --> 00:07:14.840
Like, you know, Nate's just getting started still in grad school.

00:07:15.060 --> 00:07:20.100
Nathaniel's been out for, you know, a while, and I'm, you know, tenured heading towards full.

00:07:20.200 --> 00:07:22.160
So you've got three folks at different stages.

00:07:22.500 --> 00:07:27.200
And there aren't really platforms for having the kind of conversations

00:07:27.200 --> 00:07:30.560
about these conceptual questions.

00:07:31.240 --> 00:07:34.600
You know, like, conferences, I guess, theoretically could work that way.

00:07:35.260 --> 00:07:39.380
They just haven't, in my experience, because someone goes and gives their work,

00:07:39.420 --> 00:07:40.780
and then you respond to their work.

00:07:40.860 --> 00:07:44.320
So what you don't have is people thinking through things together.

00:07:44.840 --> 00:07:49.000
You have, here's my version of things, and then other people ask questions.

00:07:49.140 --> 00:07:51.600
And then you can have good conversations, I mean, certainly.

00:07:52.320 --> 00:07:54.580
But conferences are really the only place.

00:07:54.880 --> 00:08:00.540
And so, and it doesn't, at least in my experience, it is that very, you know, unidirectional.

00:08:00.820 --> 00:08:02.760
It's like my paper and others respond.

00:08:02.880 --> 00:08:07.760
Whereas this was sort of three people at different stages just, you know, reading some stuff

00:08:07.760 --> 00:08:09.740
who have read a bunch of different things, right?

00:08:09.800 --> 00:08:16.280
As we'll become clear is that, like, you know, Nate's itinerary, conceptual itinerary is just

00:08:16.280 --> 00:08:17.160
different than mine.

00:08:17.260 --> 00:08:21.640
And you've read things that I haven't read, and you like things that I don't like, and

00:08:21.640 --> 00:08:22.300
vice versa.

00:08:22.580 --> 00:08:24.460
And so our touchstones are different.

00:08:24.880 --> 00:08:30.480
And so part of it, you know, we have to learn how to meld our, you know, our vocabularies

00:08:30.480 --> 00:08:34.460
and respond to one another and engage one another.

00:08:34.680 --> 00:08:40.860
Even though none of us have thesis statements, we all, all three of us, have intellectual projects

00:08:40.860 --> 00:08:42.600
that this intersects with.

00:08:42.660 --> 00:08:45.040
So you guys talked for a moment about yours.

00:08:45.120 --> 00:08:50.920
For me, the biggest thing is that I have been, for my entire sort of professional intellectual

00:08:50.920 --> 00:08:54.880
life, been kind of consumed with this question of what Nietzschean affirmation is.

00:08:55.440 --> 00:08:59.700
And a big component of that is thinking its relationship to negation.

00:09:00.440 --> 00:09:06.180
And I have had a, I haven't really had good purchase for how to think that, you know, and

00:09:06.180 --> 00:09:10.100
It's specifically Nietzsche in that regard of the guy who's like, you know, he's one of

00:09:10.100 --> 00:09:15.160
the most polemical thinkers around and dismisses all kinds of stuff and yet always says, what

00:09:15.160 --> 00:09:16.420
do I have to do with negation?

00:09:16.500 --> 00:09:17.580
I am pure affirmation.

00:09:17.680 --> 00:09:19.200
He makes those comments all the time.

00:09:19.300 --> 00:09:21.320
And I'm like, how do you square that, right?

00:09:21.340 --> 00:09:23.020
How do you square those two things?

00:09:23.020 --> 00:09:29.200
And obviously Hegel is the figure, uh, for thinking about negation as an engine.

00:09:29.200 --> 00:09:34.000
So that, that has been the draw for me of like wanting to kind of get involved with this,

00:09:34.180 --> 00:09:36.000
this, this thinking.

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:41.160
So again, a project like that has nothing to do, for instance, with your new materialist

00:09:41.160 --> 00:09:44.680
interest, uh, Nathaniel's pedagogical, you know, interest.

00:09:44.800 --> 00:09:50.300
So it just doesn't, um, and so this was for me, at least what has been really cool about

00:09:50.300 --> 00:09:54.100
it, and I think it's what we hoped would be cool is just three folks who have read a bunch

00:09:54.100 --> 00:09:56.300
of stuff who are, who are just curious.

00:09:56.300 --> 00:10:01.080
Like none of us have really agendas that we're trying to, I mean, to a certain extent, I'm

00:10:01.080 --> 00:10:06.600
trying to get Nate away from a certain type of project, but, but not really, right?

00:10:06.600 --> 00:10:09.840
Like, um, and, and so we don't really have agendas.

00:10:09.980 --> 00:10:13.740
It's just kind of like, we're sort of, when I said before, it's not, we're not, it's not

00:10:13.740 --> 00:10:17.640
a beginner, it's not an intro to, but neither is it an expert level.

00:10:17.640 --> 00:10:22.660
It's just a kind of in the middle mix of a, a few different, you know, three different

00:10:22.660 --> 00:10:26.120
sort of mixes and throw bouncing things off of each other.

00:10:26.120 --> 00:10:31.260
And that as a mode of learning, I mean, that's where I think like, I don't come out of this

00:10:31.260 --> 00:10:36.580
saying, I, I know the institutional version of Hegel any better.

00:10:36.740 --> 00:10:37.720
I don't feel that way.

00:10:37.760 --> 00:10:41.500
Although interestingly enough, I did end up having a, I have had a recent conversation with

00:10:41.500 --> 00:10:44.060
this guy who's writing his dissertation in London on Hegel.

00:10:44.540 --> 00:10:50.380
Um, and I was like, oh, I know what he's talking about, you know, better than I did, but I

00:10:50.380 --> 00:10:51.460
don't think that's it.

00:10:51.540 --> 00:10:56.140
I think that for me, what I've come out of it with is a whole series of really provocative

00:10:56.140 --> 00:11:00.120
ideas and lines of thinking that really, I wasn't terribly familiar with that.

00:11:00.220 --> 00:11:06.100
I feel like, I mean, it, it introduced for me of like thoughts, ideas, directions.

00:11:06.620 --> 00:11:08.660
Uh, that's been the really cool thing for me.

00:11:08.660 --> 00:11:14.040
So really what I've come out of this with is seeds for, you know, essays or, I mean, I

00:11:14.040 --> 00:11:18.040
don't know if it's going to be essays or it's just sort of things to scribble around about

00:11:18.040 --> 00:11:19.120
and think about maybe.

00:11:19.780 --> 00:11:20.680
Um, but yeah.

00:11:20.800 --> 00:11:25.700
Well, I mean, I would reiterate that, you know, none of us have a thesis statement or a claim

00:11:25.700 --> 00:11:28.820
or a project that we are trying to articulate to each other.

00:11:28.900 --> 00:11:34.280
I mean, this project that the podcast as a project, you know, obviously intersects our own independent,

00:11:34.280 --> 00:11:41.960
um, uh, enterprises, but it's not a means by which we are realizing any of those things.

00:11:41.960 --> 00:11:45.360
We're not trying to make our arguments to each other.

00:11:45.360 --> 00:11:51.020
And, you know, so on the one hand, I think I really like that Thinking With title as a,

00:11:51.020 --> 00:11:52.800
as a provocation in a couple of ways.

00:11:52.880 --> 00:11:58.180
One, it is that we aren't trying to teach something that we have mastery of.

00:11:58.180 --> 00:12:02.640
On the other hand, it functions as, I think, an invitation.

00:12:03.460 --> 00:12:12.560
I think it, in, if it positions our, the three of us to each other and the three of us to

00:12:12.560 --> 00:12:21.060
the text and the three of us to the, our audience as an invitation to think along, to think within

00:12:21.060 --> 00:12:25.760
this kind of circuitry that we have developed.

00:12:25.760 --> 00:12:33.180
Um, and, and, and as an invitation, I mean, I think that that has had a, um, a really powerful

00:12:33.180 --> 00:12:43.020
pedagogical, um, uh, there's been a very powerful pedagogical dimension to these sessions with

00:12:43.020 --> 00:12:52.360
each other in that it, um, uh, it or, I know it orients me differently to the two of you and

00:12:52.360 --> 00:13:00.540
to the, the, the Hegel text where, you know, I, I, I've found that I have become more willing and

00:13:00.540 --> 00:13:08.020
more interested in allowing, um, y'all's comments and perspectives to sort of hit me.

00:13:08.020 --> 00:13:13.720
I don't need, there's nothing, I feel less defensive when I'm doing these, um, these podcasts

00:13:13.720 --> 00:13:17.820
because I'm, I, I'm not, I'm not advancing something that I need to defend.

00:13:18.100 --> 00:13:21.280
I, I, I feel like in some ways I'm more porous in this way.

00:13:21.960 --> 00:13:28.420
Um, and that, that's, you know, we had this conversation when we listened to the first

00:13:28.420 --> 00:13:31.620
couple of episodes, like, wow, none of us are listening to each other.

00:13:32.060 --> 00:13:37.100
Uh, and then, and one, I think that we've gotten better at listening to each other and gotten

00:13:37.100 --> 00:13:40.560
better at being, learning to be affected by each other.

00:13:41.020 --> 00:13:47.040
Um, on the other hand, John and I had this conversation, um, via text of a week or so

00:13:47.040 --> 00:13:51.940
ago, just about the very question of conversation, like the, the listening model of conversation

00:13:51.940 --> 00:13:57.360
where, you know, the idea is I say something and everyone else sort of decodes what I said

00:13:57.360 --> 00:13:59.880
and then attends to the content of what I said.

00:13:59.880 --> 00:14:03.320
And, and, and what was sort of, I think what we've sort of discovered in editing these and

00:14:03.320 --> 00:14:10.760
listening back to the podcast is that listening, I don't think listening is so much what is

00:14:10.760 --> 00:14:17.860
happening in, in those interactions that we are poking and potting, prodding and provoking

00:14:17.860 --> 00:14:25.740
and, you know, each other and eliciting responses and, you know, not eliciting predetermined responses,

00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:28.920
but eliciting responses nonetheless.

00:14:29.320 --> 00:14:37.300
And, you know, um, I think that that sort of reveals a very interesting dimension of care

00:14:37.300 --> 00:14:45.540
and nuance in the way that we have built an intellectual set of relationships.

00:14:45.540 --> 00:14:52.560
And I, I, so I just think, you know, you mentioned, you know, my, my scholarly pursuits tend to

00:14:52.560 --> 00:14:54.880
focus on pedagogical questions.

00:14:54.880 --> 00:15:00.960
And, and one of the most central ones is how does, how do our orientations and styles of

00:15:00.960 --> 00:15:07.220
writing and speaking and, and the forms of our written engagement, how do they work on

00:15:07.220 --> 00:15:13.180
us pedagogically to shape and habitually our orientation to, to others, to otherness.

00:15:13.700 --> 00:15:18.380
And, you know, I, I think that this has been a profound lesson in, in exactly, you know,

00:15:18.380 --> 00:15:19.960
along those lines.

00:15:21.020 --> 00:15:26.660
And one of the, I mean, the other impetus for me to just to talk about Hegel is that our

00:15:26.660 --> 00:15:30.620
field doesn't really have an orientation towards Hegel, broadly speaking.

00:15:31.040 --> 00:15:36.420
I mean, for the field of philosophy, Hegel is a singular figure, uh, and the importance of

00:15:36.420 --> 00:15:37.620
Hegel is basically on question.

00:15:37.620 --> 00:15:41.200
But for rhetoric, it's much, it's much more confusing for me.

00:15:41.300 --> 00:15:42.960
He's basically ignored, right?

00:15:43.040 --> 00:15:48.620
I mean, like he's either sort of viciously denied as a figure for a kind of humanist mode

00:15:48.620 --> 00:15:52.960
of thinking that we have assumed to have gotten past, right?

00:15:53.040 --> 00:15:54.500
Or he's simply ignored.

00:15:55.000 --> 00:15:59.260
And so I think for me, again, it, this doesn't, it doesn't have to, he doesn't have to function

00:15:59.260 --> 00:16:00.340
this way for you guys.

00:16:00.340 --> 00:16:06.280
But for me, he continually functions basically as a warning, as a, as a warning of a figure

00:16:06.280 --> 00:16:13.760
for a kind of thinking that, that I presume still kind of exists and, and infects and infiltrates,

00:16:13.760 --> 00:16:20.900
um, some of the, what I, what I continue to call a more materialist bent, uh, of like contemporary

00:16:20.900 --> 00:16:21.520
theory.

00:16:22.200 --> 00:16:28.380
So, I mean, we, we talk about in most of these, uh, podcasts, we come back to this point

00:16:28.380 --> 00:16:33.260
where, I mean, you guys, you guys are agitated by Hegel and I am as well.

00:16:33.380 --> 00:16:37.180
I, I kind of play the, the defender occasionally, right?

00:16:37.200 --> 00:16:39.080
Or the foil for, for you guys.

00:16:39.080 --> 00:16:45.340
But I mean, I'm basically on board with your suspicions, but my orientation is to kind of

00:16:45.340 --> 00:16:49.820
lean into those suspicions and say that they, you know, Hegel is still with us.

00:16:49.820 --> 00:16:54.220
That's, that's probably a bad thing, but I think we need to still attend to that, you

00:16:54.220 --> 00:16:54.980
know, to.

00:16:55.340 --> 00:17:00.120
I mean, I, uh, bracketing Hegel for a second and, but this is responding to what you're

00:17:00.120 --> 00:17:00.560
saying.

00:17:01.040 --> 00:17:08.580
Um, I, I feel like the most, um, satisfying and compelling, uh, intellectual interactions

00:17:08.580 --> 00:17:13.480
I've had in my professional career have almost all been when I'm writing almost all.

00:17:14.040 --> 00:17:17.260
Um, and I say, in other words, not in a classroom, right?

00:17:17.260 --> 00:17:18.840
It just doesn't happen very often.

00:17:18.840 --> 00:17:21.060
It does sometimes, but, but not very often.

00:17:21.360 --> 00:17:26.760
And this is the first sort of non-writing interaction that has felt like writing.

00:17:27.400 --> 00:17:32.960
Um, so, so that in, in what I like about when I write is that the writing talks back to me

00:17:32.960 --> 00:17:36.620
and it, it, it leads me down directions that I'm like, I'm not sure if I wanted to go there

00:17:36.620 --> 00:17:40.400
and, and, and you guys are serving that function, right?

00:17:40.400 --> 00:17:46.260
Like, I mean, in terms of my thinking that this is for me, at least this has been the

00:17:46.260 --> 00:17:53.160
only kind of intellectual sort of, you know, stabilized space, repeated space or repeated

00:17:53.160 --> 00:17:57.980
interactions that feels that I experienced like the experience of writing.

00:17:58.520 --> 00:18:03.500
And, and for that, I mean, it's invaluable to me in that regard because I, you don't, again,

00:18:03.500 --> 00:18:07.260
you do get that sometimes in a classroom, there'll be moments, you know, where it's like, okay,

00:18:07.260 --> 00:18:11.140
it's clicking and people are engaging, but it doesn't happen regularly.

00:18:11.680 --> 00:18:15.600
And it's certainly not something that you can program because it's so dependent on who happens

00:18:15.600 --> 00:18:19.780
to be in your classroom and who has slept well that day and who's eaten and, you know,

00:18:19.840 --> 00:18:20.700
those kinds of things.

00:18:21.100 --> 00:18:25.580
Um, and, and so to me, I mean, I, that's how I think of this is I feel like we're writing,

00:18:25.820 --> 00:18:31.020
like not we're preparing to write, but, but we're writing and that's what we're doing in

00:18:31.020 --> 00:18:31.160
here.

00:18:31.240 --> 00:18:35.100
So there's a way in which, you know, you can certainly make the argument that these are, um,

